context: <a0_0><b5_0>Charles Pollak<b5_0/><a0_0/> (born Karol Pollak), the inventor of the first electrolytic capacitors, found out that the oxide layer on an aluminum anode remained stable in <a1_0>a <b6_0>neutral or alkaline electrolyte<b6_0/><a1_0/>, even when the power was switched off. <a2_0>In 1896<a2_0/> he filed a <b7_0>patent for an "Electric liquid capacitor with aluminum electrodes."<b7_0/> <a3_0><b8_0>Solid electrolyte tantalum capacitors<b8_0/><a3_0/> were invented by Bell Laboratories in the early 1950s as a miniaturized and more reliable low-voltage support capacitor <a4_0><b9_0>to complement their newly invented transistor<b9_0/><a4_0/>.
